s2tt:
Loving the people, the tribes submit;
Far and near as one, to the king they commit.
Phoenixes sing in bamboos, white colts graze;
Plants thrive in kindness, all lands in praise.
This body and hair, from parents we owe;
With reverence nourished, how dare we mar them so.
Women admire chastity, men talent and grace;

When faults are known, then set them right;
When arts are gained, then don't forget.
Don't talk about others' short;
Don't boast about your own forte.
Be trustworthy and be sincere;
Be tolerant and be sincere.
The ink bewails silk dyed amiss;
The ode lauds lamb's innocence.
The virtuous are worth our praise;
The sage-like are worth our days.
With virtue, fame will be attained;
With uprightness, respect is gained.
In empty vale sound travels far;
In empty hall echoes are heard.

s2tt_r:
手针制满，逐物意移；笺纸雅操，皓绝字迷；都邑华夏，东西二京；贝蒙面落，符蔚俱精；宫殿盘郁，楼观飞惊；图写禽兽，画彩仙灵；秉设旁启，甲帐对盈。

译文：
Needlework fills hands, chasing objects' intent shifts; 
Ink and paper, elegant, white and clear, words enthrall; 
Capital, China's heart, east and west, two capitals; 
Bemont's face falls, symbols and runes both refined; 
Palaces twist and turn, towers soar and shock; 
Paintings depict beasts, colors and spirits shine; 
Sides set up, armor-like curtains align.

原文：
教不严，师之惰；子不学，非所宜；幼不学，老何为？玉不琢，不成器；人不学，不知义。为人子，方少时，亲师友，习礼仪。香九龄，能温席，孝于亲，所当执。

译文：
Education without strictness, teacher's laziness;
Children not learning, not appropriate;
Young not studying, old what for?
Unpolished jade, not into a tool;
People not learning, not knowing righteousness.
As a child, respect teachers and friends, learn manners.
Xiang Jiuling, can warm the bed, filial piety to parents, should be held.

s2tt:
At four, he shared pears with grace;
To elders, yielding took first place.
First filial love and brotherhood,
Then knowledge for the greater good.
From one to ten, from ten to score,
From hundreds on to thousands more.
Three powers: heaven, earth, and man;
Three lights: the moon, the sun, the span;
Three bonds: the king, the subject true,
And husband-wife's bond, tried and true.

Upon the sea the moon shines bright;
We gaze on it far, far apart.
My love would grudge the long, long night;
From dusk to dawn she'd pine apart.
Put out the candle, love the light;
Put on my robe, I feel the dew.
Can I hand you the moon so bright?
I'd go to bed to dream of you.

Fire spouts, gold stars to heaven fly;
Twelve streets with smoke and flame glow high.
The sun sinks west, cold gleams the light;
God silent stands in voiceless plight.
Dark clouds hang thick like siege arrayed;
The eunuch-star in blood displayed.
The purple air moves with the throne;
Evil rays shoot stars overthrown.
In every house blood boils like spring;
On every side wronged voices ring.

On marble steps no footfall sounds;
Through beaded screens but shadow flits around.
When clashing blades in courtyard clang,
Head severed from the body in a twinkling.
Looking up, she veils her face and cries;
Sisters and sisters-in-law into the well dive.
The northern neighbor's wife is urged to flee;
She loosens her cloudlike hair and wipes her eyebrows green.
The gate is battered down, the din draws near;
She climbs up the roof, unaware of fear.

On Hanyuan Hall foxes and hares run;
Before Blossom Tower thorns o'ergrown.
All former splendor's buried and gone;
I see but dreariness left alone.
The brocades in store are burnt to ashes grey;
The nobles' bones on the street are trodden away.
At dawn I left the city's eastern gate;
The misty plain looks like a frontier state.
I see patrols now and then by roadside drear;
No host nor guest is seen on hillside here.

Before the shrine, old cypress stands half dead;
In golden censers, dust veils incense red.
Since rebel hordes o'erran the Middle Land,
Dark wind and rain have swept the sky and strand.
The holy water could not break the spell;
The magic soldiers on the wall fought not well.
In peace we enjoyed offerings in vain;
In war we could not help to ease the pain.
Ashamed of my incompetence as god,
I'll hide myself deep in the mountains' sod.

My wealth is gone, my family fled;
In lonely age I'm left in dread.
Yet my own grief is not the worst;
In hills more families are cursed.
At dawn I search for herbs for food;
At night I sleep in reeds and dew.
Hearing the old man's tale of woe,
My tears like streams unceasing flow.
Outside I hear but owls' harsh cries;
Where can I flee 'neath these sad skies?

The traveler sees Luo Fu, puts down his load and strokes his beard;
The youth sees Luo Fu, doffs his cap and shows his headgear.
The ploughman forgets his plough, the hoer forgets his hoe;
Back home, they blame each other, but for watching Luo Fu.
The lord comes from the south, his five steeds halt and wait;
He sends a man to ask whose beauty is so great.

A thousand horsemen eastward ride;
My husband is their foremost guide.
How to pick my lord from the rest?
On white steed he is the best,
With black colt following behind,
His horse's tail with blue silk twined,
Its head with golden gear confined.
At his waist hangs a precious sword
Worth more than a thousand hoard.
At fifteen he was a county clerk;
At twenty he served in the imperial hall;
At thirty he was a chamberlain dark;
At forty he was lord of the capital.

I long for the fair one, yet she does not appear;
Facing the wind, I sing aloud in sorrow clear.
With feather canopy and banners green in hue,
I climb the ninefold heaven to touch the star anew.
Holding a long sword, I protect the young and fair;
You alone are fit to rule with just and tender care.

My spirit towers o'er the poets old;
My eyes disdain the walls of laureates bold.
I failed in the exam though I did my best;
I left the capital, my mind distressed.
I roamed between Qi and Zhao, free and unrest,
In furs and on horseback, I did what I pleased.
I sang on the terrace in spring breeze;
I hunted by green mounds when winter did freeze.
I called my falcon in the wood of black steed;
I chased wild beasts on cloud-and-snow-clad mead.
I shot flying birds, giving my horse free rein;
I raised my arm and brought down birds in rain.

On Baidi's walls spring grass grows green;
Below White Salt Mount clear waves are seen.
Southerners come up and sing a song;
Northerners feel homesick all day long.
Red flowers bloom over the hill;
Spring water against it flows still.
Red flowers fade as my gallant's will;
My grief lasts like water flowing still.
The riverside pavilion's steeped in rain;
The western stream ripples in vain.

In hardship, a poor scholar loses his post, his heart in unrest;
In solitude, a wanderer finds no friend, by fate oppressed.
In sorrow, he laments his own plight, with heavy sighs confessed.
Swallows fly south, leaving their nests in graceful, parting flight;
Cicadas fall silent, hushed in the fading autumn light.
Wild geese head south with mournful cries, a long and weary train;
Pheasants chatter with plaintive notes, singing a sad refrain.
Alone, I stay awake till dawn, unable to find rest,
Grieving for crickets that march through the night without a nest.

I long to see you, to tell my heart;
But your heart and mine are far apart.
My carriage ready, I must depart.
Not seeing you, how sad I am at heart!
Leaning on the door, I heave long sighs;
My tears stream down and wet the shaft.
I cannot sever our fond ties;
My mind is lost in a maze, waft.
When can I end my self-pity?
My heart beats fast, sincere and true.

Heaven shares the four seasons fair and square;
I grieve alone o'er autumn sad and bare.
White dew descends on grass and trees around;
The plane and catalpa wither on the ground.
The bright and glorious day has passed away;
The long, long night will hold its sway.
When flowers and leaves were in their prime,
I'm sad to see their fall in time.
Autumn warns with white dew cold;
Winter adds hoar frost severe.

The floating clouds have blocked the light,
And left the world in endless night.
The ancient kings chose men of worth,
And laid aside all care on earth.
They had no fear of blame or hate;
Why should they be in anxious state?
A steed will run of its own will;
Why should the rider use the goad still?
The city walls can't be relied;
What use is armor fortified?

Red ants like elephants swarm the land;
Black wasps like gourds in swarms expand.
No crops will grow, but reeds they eat;
The soil corrodes the traveler's feet.
No water can be found for thirst;
Vast wilderness, by bounds uncurst.
O soul, come back! Lest you be slain,
To northern wilds don't stray again.

In high hall wine is laid out fine;
My friends and kin follow me to dine.
From kitchen come rich dishes rare,
Roast mutton and fat calf so fair.
The Qin lute plays with vigor strong;
The Qi zither sings a soft song.
Dancers perform with wondrous art;
Famed singers play their tuneful part.
Three rounds of wine we drink with cheer,
Our belts loosened, we taste each cheer.
The host offers gifts rich and grand;
The guests wish him a life long and grand.

What left me yesterday can be retained no more;
What troubles me today may my mind deeply bore.
In autumn wind for miles and miles wild geese fly away;
Let us drink to our hearts' content in towers high, I pray!
Your writing's crowned with literary grace supreme;
My style is like the poet's in a clear-cut dream.
Both of us have an ideal high and would fly;
We'd bring down the bright moon from the sky.

Fish in the trap, bream and shark;
My lord has wine, fine and much.
Fish in the trap, carp and chub;
My lord has wine, much and fine.
Fish in the trap, eel and tench;
My lord has wine, fine and fresh.
How rich the catch, how good the cheer!
How fine the feast, how full the cheer!

Firm was the Duke Liu, not for ease he'd stay.  
He marked the bounds, he fixed the border line;  
He stored the grain, he filled the barns with hay;  
He packed provisions in the sack and twine.  
To gather people and to spread his fame,  
He strung his bow and arrows, spear and blade;  
Then forth he marched, his purpose to proclaim.  

Firm was the Duke Liu, to the plain he came.  
The people thronged, a prosperous, teeming band;  
Contented, settled, free from sigh and blame,  
They followed him to cultivate the land.

Bless this central land, let no harm befall;
Check not the crafty, nor let flatterers enthrall.
Repress the cruel, keep the state from overthrow;
The king would cherish you, thus my counsel I bestow.

I see my lord, four steeds he rides;
Four steeds he rides, six reins like tides.
To left, to left, he turns with grace;
To right, to right, he keeps his pace.
As he commands both left and right,
He follows rules with pure delight.

The Xu land is subdued, the Son of Heaven's might;
All quarters pacified, Xu comes to court in sight.
Xu's loyalty stands true, the King commands the right.

My axe is broken, my hatchet worn;
The Duke to east goes, kingdoms to warn.
Alas for us men, our fate so forlorn!

My axe is broken, my spade worn out;
The Duke to east goes, to quell the rout.
Alas for us men, our fate in doubt!

My axe is broken, my chisel worn;
The Duke to east goes, rebellion torn.
Alas for us men, in hardship born!

Fierce the host, by Shao led to the fore;
High and low leveled, streams and springs clear once more.
Shao's great work done, the king's heart is at rest.

Eastward the Brocade River flows around Brocade Town;
The Star Bridge hangs northward like stars in a crown.
From all four seas to the holy lord they come;
Below Mount Emei stands the immortal home.

Through Sword Gate Pass, the north gate of Shu, the emperor's steeds return like clouds in view.  
The young prince in Chang'an ascends the throne;  
Two suns and moons together brightly shone.

Old scrolls dusted, I read with care;
Lute awaits the moon to play its air.
Peach Blossom Spring hides names of old;
Pine trees guard tales by Qin foretold.
Few return to this vale deep;
Green hills chill where sunbeams sleep.
I envy your retreat, so high,
Gazing where white clouds touch the sky.

Through winding crags a narrow path winds low;
Cloud-veiled woods hide the hall where scriptures grow.
Immortal minstrels play on pipes unseen;
Celestial maids kneel down with incense sheen.
Beyond bamboos peaks greet the morning ray;
Through shades of vines cool water winds its way.
How long in meditation has he sat?
The path with vernal blooms is fragrant that.

Jade incense smoke blends in the air;
Glass floor spreads smooth and bright and fair.
Dragon halls with pillars stand high;
Tiered eaves touch tigers' dens nearby.
In quiet vale but pines sough long;
In deep hills you hear no birds' song.
Before the door jade peaks uprear;
Through woods gold streams flow bright and clear.
Cloud-veiled is the road to the town;
Beyond rain the plain's looking down.
The wild geese bring fruit as their prize;
The roe treads on blooms 'neath the skies.

Silk reels in bamboo grove, the loom stands still;
Cicadas shrill in slanting sun on the hill.
Peach gum gleams like amber in summer's breath;
I teach the southern hands to melons tend.

Spring water newborn, young swallows fly;
Yellow bees, small tails, to flowers hie.
Through window, distant hues veil study's screen;
Fish kiss sweet hooks by rocky ledge serene.

Hills and streams stretch far beyond the sight;
Towers and terraces rise high in clouds bright.
The garden bathes in sunlight and moonlight;
Its view outshines all works of art and might.

The bridal room, with jewels cold;
The jade hall, autumn wind bold.
O'er Qin land should the crescent gleam;
The Dragon Pool floods the old dream.
My boat tonight is bound afar;
The clepsydra drips as they are.
North of Mount Yellow, miles and miles,
'Mong royal tombs white dew piles.

Autumn waters join the ditches wide;
A small boat nears the city side.
At dusk, cool air, men wash their steeds;
In dense woods cicadas sing in reeds.
The caltrops ripen in the rain;
The rush grows wild in August plain.
At dawn white dew begins to fall;
I think of my old rug in hall.

Amid dense clouds woods hide away;
O'er endless hills rain clouds hold sway.
The wind-blown door flaps to and fro;
The water birds come, then they go.
Weavers' looms sound like shuttles' beat;
Woodmen's boats row with oars so fleet.
The coolness breaks the summer's heat;
My weary heart longs for a seat.

The setting sun in limpid river glows;  
The southern maid with slender waist sings sweet.  
Since childhood she has plucked the lotus rose;  
At fifteen she can ride the tides with fleet.

High roll the broidered screen by poolside view;
Rain flips up lotus leaves with pearls in dew.
The summer heat is gone when cool grows night;
Sweet breeze o'er water wafts with lotus light.
Why should I grieve o'er bygone days in vain?
How can I not remember with heart pain?
Time hastens on and presses me with might;
Before I know it, autumn's in my sight.

Grieving, I ask the sky above,
Vast and blue, with no path to my love.
I look up to clouds and mist in vain;
Who'll convey my grief in this refrain?
On city walls war-fires never die;
On battlefields when will men not die?
At dawn through gates killing airs blow;
At night the moon hears wild winds blow.
My homeland's cut off, no news come;
I weep in silence, my breath grows numb.

Then palaces and halls, on hills and vales, are built;
With double-eaved roofs and winding corridors, they're gilt.
The painted rafters and jade inlaid walls
Are linked by passageways and decorated halls.
The winding corridors go round and round;
It takes a day to travel from one end to the other bound.
On hilltops built, the terraced houses rise;
The rock-hewn chambers are lost to the eyes.
Looking down, you see nothing in the misty deep;
Looking up, you can touch the painted rafters steep.

Swift stars pass through the women's bower;
Rainbow arches o'er the watch tower.
Green dragons coil in eastern hall;
White elephants walk in west hall.
Immortals rest in leisure hours
Or bask in sunshine in south bowers.
Sweet springs bubble in chambers clear;
Through central courtyard streams flow here.
Rocks piled on rocks form cragged steep;
Precipices stand rugged and deep.

Amid white clouds the northern hills lie;
A hermit there enjoys his leisure high.
I climb up high to gaze my fill;
My heart goes with wild geese until
They disappear from sight.
My sorrow grows with twilight;
My joy comes with autumn clear.
I see the woodmen go home here and there,
Resting on sand or ferry flat.
The sky-bound trees look like low bushes green;
The moon-like river islets white are seen.
When can I bring wine here
To get drunk on Mountain-Climbing Day?

On the Jianghan lords, military might is weighed;
At the Xihue hosts, jade tokens are displayed.
Then court and country in joy and mirth parade,
With music played in gardens and on balustrade.
The streets are thronged with caps and carriages in view;
The doors become the seats of scholars old and new.
The blooming gardens stretch to seaside Haizhou;
The pool with railings spans the riverside anew.
At eastern gate a bridge is paved with stones like whips;
At southern end a bronze pillar for ships.
Ten thousand orange trees in gardens grow;
A thousand households with bamboos aglow.

Spring waters from Moon Gorge flow;
Where will my boat drift? I don't know.
It's time for peach blossoms to fall,
Yet still green waves of Brocade call.
The waves so green and bright appear,
Blending with sky far and near.
Winding Bashan Mountains fade away;
Over Chu clouds leisurely sway.
Snow-lit sands gather wild geese in flight;
From blooming vales orioles take flight.
The fragrant isle has passed from view;
Greeting me are trees green and new.

To build a weir, clouds churn the stream;
Startled by cold rains of fourth moon's gleam.
Green rills hide dragons' dens below;
Bamboo-rock hills forbid to go.

Six monarchs reigned, then left the place;
The palace gate was closed apace.
The young who came and went would say
The Flower Tower was in decay.
Last year an envoy came to cut bamboos;
I followed him when the gate was open thus.
The ponds were overgrown with thorns and weeds;
Foxes and hares ran wild among the trees.
The dancing hall was ruined, its base left there;
The green gauze still hung on the windows fair.

The Royal Garden looks like a picture fine;
The palace tiles like water flow.
The Hall of Light stands by the waterside;
The Tower of Moonlight will grow.
At night the mirror opens, phoenix flies;
In winter furs are offered by the cock.
Half-drunk, the courtiers feast their eyes;
The emperor's carefree on the rock.

Xia Ji ruined two states, then fled to be a witch's bride;  
Xi Shi left Gusu's towers, on a boat with her lover to hide.  
Wei Bao, captive in weaving halls, laid Han's peace profound;  
By error placed in royal rolls, two courts her virtue crowned.  
Guangwu, heir to Gaozu's line, from Lady Tang was born;  
Coral shattered Qi's high reign, to grind millet, low and worn.

Insects rest, wild geese ail, red shoots appear;  
The wind turns back, sees guests off, blows dim fire drear.  
In search of old tales, waves churn, broken arrows lie;  
Blades chipped, crimson cracks, once cut through flesh nearby.  
A lad on horseback, east and south of the town,  
Urges me to trade gold for bamboo renown.

A lonely town three days in wind and rain;
The market small with vegetables but vain.
Two water birds o'er far-flung streams and hills;
A lonely heron free from worldly ills.
An old man comes to gather net aside;
I stand by stream, no fish to be my guide.
What's done will not be done again, alas!
At dusk I read old books by window glass.

Hills bare, late autumn seen in yellow dye;
Insects urge maids to sew clothes warm and high.
An old pine in cloud vale has seen long years;
No thousand oxen could move it with the stream.

A sickly guest, I seldom climb the height;
I seek the Southern Tower in southern site.
On roaring waves nine roads slowly go;
Across the stream a thousand ships in row.
From temple towers bells urge night and day;
O'er village walls clouds rise and pass away.
My hair turns grey, but not my spirit proud.
Drunk, I play flute beneath the banyan shroud.

March breeze melts snow away;
Hunan hills gleam emerald spray.
A lonely flute is heard unseen;
Plum blooms fall o'er the bridge in sheen.

On duty, sleep I cannot find;
At midnight still I journey alone.
Singing for posts is not my mind;
To plough and reap I am prone.
I'll cast my official hat away,
And to my humble cottage return.
No high position can make me stay;
In truth and simplicity I'll sojourn.

The truth, as trunk, stands firm and high;
The words, as boughs, hang down and multiply.
If mind and face are in accord,
Each change of mind will face afford.
When thought on pleasure goes, one smiles;
When sorrow's told, one sighs for miles.
Sometimes the pen just flows with ease;
Sometimes it halts and seems to freeze.
How happy is the writer's state!
The sages may appreciate.

Light robes tucked, I retrace my way;
I sigh to see the sun's last ray.
I pace and pause, forget my goal;
My face is sad, my mournful soul.
Leaves rustle down from boughs on high;
The air grows chill as they pass by.
The sun with its shadow sinks low;
The moon with fair clouds vies in glow.
Birds sadly sing, each flies alone;
Beasts seek in vain mates of their own.

The sacred turtle, though long-lived, must die;
The soaring serpent mounts in mist, but turns to dust.
An old steed in the stable still aspires to gallop a thousand miles;
A hero in his twilight years retains his lofty dreams.
Our span of life, long or short, does not rest with Heaven alone;
He who finds joy in health may enjoy lasting years.
How happy I feel to chant this song of mine!

The fishermen's song goes thus:
Of the three Gorges the Witch Gorge is longest;
Hearing the gibbons' wails, you'll wet your vest.

Hard to meet, and hard to part,
The east wind languid, flowers fade apart.
The silkworm's thread ends only when death comes;
The candle's tears dry just in dying flames.
At dawn I fear my mirrored hair turns grey;
At night you'd feel the chill in moonlight's ray.
To the three fairy hills it is not far;
Would the blue bird oft fly to where you are?

The boiling spring no longer flows;
The scorching wind no longer blows.
The northern doors are sealed with clay;
The naked tribes in furs array.
Then clouds o'er rivers and seas rise;
The northern desert sandstorm flies.
The mist and haze in thick array
Veil the bright sun and hide the ray.
The sleet falls first with rustling sound;
Then snowflakes whirl and dance around.
They look like stars scattered in flight,
Or mist and haze in dim twilight.

I'd love to roam with gulls o'er Eastern Sea,  
And gather herbs on Western Hill with thee.  
You dwell in mountains, free from worldly strife;  
I drift in dust, leading a dragon's life.  
We can't enjoy fair scenes side by side;  
At home alone I pass my days with pride.  
Birds sing amid the eaveside trees in view;  
Flowers fall on books beneath my window, too.  
I see green bamboos mirrored in the stream;  
Red lotus peeps out from the hill, agleam.  
I sing and smile while gathering herbs sweet;  
How can I forget you when we don't meet?

Grass bends, clouds hang low, the hunt's ring draws near;
Bowstrings hum, steeds like arrows fly without fear.
Laughing, I call my train to load the game here.
Naught matters more than skill and might so clear;
Cherish youth's prime, for life is but a year.
How can one, white-haired, 'neath book-curtains appear?

The sky is veiled in gloomy cloud;
A stray wild goose flies 'gainst the wind aloud.
Where can you find a shelter now?
On pathway fowlers shoot you from the bow;
In bower hands are washed with vinegar.
Tonight we'll feast more than we did before.

Sleepless, a homesick traveler lies;
At midnight toward home he turns his eyes.
The moonbeams blend with sand and waters white;
The sail with frost is laden in my sight.
The river broadens as it nears the sea;
The autumn night is longer, it seems to me.
After sailing on mist-veiled waves for a moon,
I have not reached my destination soon.

The court is plagued by woes untold;
All generals high posts now hold.
To northern land envoys are sent;
To rule the south, men eloquent.
The state needs talents to restore;
You should rise up and do much more.
With sword you'll make a hero great;
Your carriage will leave dust and hate.
War has broken the land in two;
The treasury's empty in view.
All officers should be honest and bright;
All corvees should be equal and right.

Along the stream my robe is wet;
At noon the mist begins to set.
In winter warm, mosquitoes throng;
Far from men, ducks make wild song.
I climb and see clouds darken the sky;
I lean and see the steep bank high.
By the post-house withered willow trees stand;
Beside the town light smoke veils the land.
How beautiful the rivershore!
I feast my eyes on the grandeur.
The mountains look drear and far away;
The river spreads out in sunset ray.

For Confucius I grieve at the time ill-spent;
Like Wang Can I leave my homeland with lament.
My life is but a drifting boat;
What I have undergone makes me sigh afloat.

The starry envoy, bound, can't turn his flight;  
Two lads present the jade-green coach so bright.  
Beneath nine-branched lamps, at the golden hall he bows;  
Amid tri-colored clouds, he serves the jade towers.  
The phoenix maid, wild-hearted, long has been away;  
The moon goddess, lone-dwelling, would join his play.  
Had she then loved the prince of Han with all her heart,  
Her buried bones to ash would nurse endless regret.

Vast, vast the cold stream flows;
Dim, dim the autumn rain glows.
You ask where South Hill lies;
Beyond white clouds it flies.

Dewdrops fall, my robe they wet;
The moon ascends, a silver plate.
Awake to elders' call, I fret
Lest sheep and cattle trample my gate.
Thus I rise, and sing this lay:
The moon is bright, stars are few;
You greet my going, bid adieu.
The year grows late, plants decay;
Return, return, do not stay
In yellow mud for long delay.

Red leaves, crows, by waterside rest;
Snow on pines wakes me drunk from sleep.
Peach blossoms fall on running stream;
Need immortals in Fairyland dwell?
Clear hills and streams, I'm soiled with dust;
Though there's a way, I cannot go.
I give you back the picture with sighs;
My mountain friend would call me back.

After rain, duckweeds reunite;
Frogs croak from left and right.
Begonia's dream is done;
Green mume is tasted new.
Leaning on cane, I pick wild herbs in the sun;
On the swing, no maiden's in view.
Only the peony fair
Is left to crown late spring with care.

Red flags and blue canopies gleam and fade;
Black sands and white waves clash and invade.
Life's meetings, as of old, are hard to secure;
Such scene and such trip, can we have both, I'm not sure.
I wish you'd light more candles to hear my song,
And see white-gowned men like cranes outside throng.

At dawn I climb the hundred-foot tower high;
I gaze on the road to Yan-zhi far and nigh.
Between the greenish sky the Han forts stand;
The Tartar's sky is swept as with white sand.
I call to mind the general brave and bold,
Who made incessant war in days of old.
The Tartars could not put him to defeat;
The barren hills are covered with grass sweet.
I see but wild geese fly from north to south;
How can I not feel sad and close my mouth?
The Jin emperor thought not of after-day;
His successor ended in disarray.

O'er bird's path oft we climb and rest;
Our steeds trot on with ne'er a stay.
We wind through rugged mountain crest
And pass hills rising in array.
Where rocks dash on the stream, we go;
'Mid pines in cold we wend our way.
The royal journey is not slow;
We won't turn homeward e'en today.

On New Year's Eve, 1191, I left Stone Lake for Wuxing. Passing Rainbow Bridge on a snowy night, I wrote:

Vast, vast the Misty Lake where wild geese fly;
Peak on jade peak towers in cloud-woven dress.
Lonely, lonely the long bridge in cold spring night;
Only a poet's boat comes home in loneliness.

Five years later in winter, I sailed again with my friends from Fengyu to Liangxi.

Things most hard, by Heaven's grace, are done;
The emperor came back to his throne.
The queen inside might say yes or no;
Her father outside would come or go.
How could he live in Southern Bower?
When General Gao left, sad the hour.
I wrote two chapters of history;
Du Fu sang of cuckoo with glee.
Who knows the loyal ministers' pain?
Their jewelled words are read in vain.

A star-like hut for a monk deep in the wood;
A dragon-like tower for a poet old.
The hill veiled in fine rain, long sits the guest;
The sky-linked long river, late comes the sail.
The fragrant bedroom is cut off from the world;
The marvelous painting is known to none at all.
Each cell has windows open to the breeze;
Tea is made with vine twigs under the trees.

On White King Town spring grass grows green;
Below White Salt Mount clear waves are seen.
Southerners come up and sing a song;
Northerners won't come up, for homesick long.

Through worldly flowers I see the void;
From fleeting fame I stand aloof.
In straw sandals I drink on hillside steep;
With bamboo cane I stroll in woods so deep.
My body free, my mind in peace I keep.
The lingering cold still bites with might;
The drizzling rain just clears from sight.
On mossy paper I write lines by rills;
From mist-veiled boat I hear sweet songs that trill.
Drunk or awake, we share the same delight.

The stream swells with breeze brushing the face;
The moon sets with stars studding the space.
A few boats lie across the ferry;
A flute rises o'er the hill, merry.

Red banners on city gates fly;
Spring god drives his chariot by.
Swallows chirp o'er new mud nest;
Bees grow few when flowers rest.
Dense shade of willow and locust trees;
Slight heat comes in through windows and doors.
At sunset, after bath, with ease,
I try on unlined dress once more.

Bronze drums summon the gods in rite;
Banners and canopies fill the courtyard bright.
Through waterside villages and riverside shores, thunder roars;
Chu mountains unveil in painted mist, as the storm soars.
Parting oars sound hollow, bleak and drear;
Fair faces languish, with fading makeup sheer.
Over green wheat fields, swallows glide low;
Rolling up the curtain, she faces the pearl tower in woe.

A dappled horse with golden rein,
A broidered belt with dagger vain.
In wine-cups drowned, his spirits sink;
Drawn is the sword to kill, I think.
When comes the foe in hot pursuit,
He goes afar, his sword to boot.
Thirty long years he's left his home;
Now he returns to his old dome.
He climbs the height to look around;
The capital's within his bound.
The streets stretch like a placid stream;
Twin towers like floating clouds seem.

By palace gates stand generals and ministers grand;
Along the road are ranked nobles on either hand.
At noon the court and market place are full of lords;
Their carriages and steeds flow on like streams in ford.
They dine on tripods when the bell rings for the feast;
They vie with each other to ride abreast, at least.
Why am I left alone in such a plight?
With hundred cares in my heart, sad and drear.

From hillside mumes cross the stream I come;
I love the stream nearby and mumes afar.
The stream with murmuring voice invites me to stay;
The mumes with blooming flowers call me back.

Not only spring is fair, summer is fine;
Flowers and grass at will make life divine.
The slender-stalked day-lily blooms with grace;
The smallest flower of balsam shows its face.

From West Lake I come when the moon's on the wane;
Through lotus blooms and willow trees I pass.
The fragrant world's a cool domain;
I go o'er southern hill and northern hill again.

Autumn pure won't follow the departing boat;
Red leaves fall on cold waves and float.
I dream of her green hairpin;
Complaining wild geese must have passed the southern inn.

From tall trees cicadas sing in autumn lane;
Vermilion gates stand quiet as leisure reign.
Dark ink paintings show bamboo stems, few and fine;
A shelf of books with fragrance long doth shine.
Attendants' talk and laughter show their grace;
Wild guests chant free, unrestrained in time and space.
Among these, tales of heroes I adore,
Yet fear my deeds may match their fame no more.

Through worldly strife I drift without a bound;
My heart's own history is nowhere found.
Autumn won't startle swallows in the hall;
At dusk crows on roadside trees still call.
East neighbor's widow can't be a spouse;
Deep-rooted old trees bear no flowers.
When can I vanish like swan in flight?
Bury my prime with beauty and books in night.

Unbuttoned, I climb the stone stair;
Seated, I look down on spring water fair.
Orchid-scented wine exhales in the breeze;
Pine-murmuring zither sings with wild trees.
Shadows waver beyond leaves hanging low;
Fragrance wafts before flowers in a row.
My joy is full by woods and pool at night;
From cliff to cliff rises evening smoke white.

The northern horn calls forth the chilling breeze;
The northern gate is whiter than the streams.
The sky o'erflows the road to azure seas;
The wall-top drowned in moonlight gleams.
The banners wet with dew hang down their heads;
The golden watchmen's clappers sound the night.
The serpent scales of mail the Tartar sheds;
The horse neighs o'er the tomb grass white.
Autumn is still; the banners hang down low;
The far-off sand can't tie up homesickness.
North of the tent the sky seems to end now;
Out of the frontier flows the stream's song, mute or loud.

Green trees shade villages in sight;
Sparse yellow blooms out of the way.
Green spring grass on far waterside;
Still waterfowl fly o'er the bay.

In the hot night I rise and go alone
To mount the tower and lift my robe undone.
The hills and streams are steeped in summer heat;
The Milky Way sheds down its silver light.
The crystal sun dries up the dewy sweet;
The quiet plain stops blowing wind at night.
I draw cool water from the well so deep;
I open doors to kitchen fire asleep.
Leaning on rails, I hesitate for long;
I cannot wipe off sweat, however strong.
Who knows the reason why the world is made?
I look up and ask stars for their aid.

The rain just cleared, I long to roam afar;
At sunset, I stroll to the Fool's Ferry Bar.
The ferry's low, a village path appears;
Rafts hang in chaos on trees like veneers.

The Son of Heaven holds the world in sway;
The northern tribesmen still fight night and day.
In vain brave generals and counselors boast;
A smile from Beauty calms the northern coast.

Cold town, flags flutter in frontier breeze;
Alone I lean on tower, gaze in unease.
Tang's land stretches ten thousand miles afar;
Jin's heroes' souls shine like eternal star.
Heart-torn, I can't bear border steeds' sad neigh;
Past deeds are questioned by wild geese in flight.
I'd cast off scholar's cap for arms to wield,
With halberd long and mighty bow to wield.

Thresh the wheat, thresh the wheat,
Thump and thud, beat on beat,
Echoing north and south of the hill.
In April the sun rises northeast still,
Just off the sea, the wheat is green and tender;
At zenith, it turns ripe in golden splendor.
The nightjar urges, sleepless night we keep;
Bamboo partridge calls rain, clouds dark and deep.
The elder wife, sickle on waist, goes out;
The younger follows, baskets roundabout.
On the ridge, green ears she first strips bare;
Down the ridge, she binds them then and there.

A youth of courage bold and high,
Brave, keen, and ready to defy.
With sword in hand he left his home;
Besieged, he stood with walls of loam.
On River Liao he slew the foe;
On fishing shore he ceased the blow.
His golden armor glistened bright;
In sable coat he was a knight.
Returning, he went hunting still;
His arrows flew with speed and skill.
Where hound and falcon swiftly flew,
Foxes and hares in grass he slew.

At night the flying squirrels cry;
By day the streams and gullies sigh.
The vernal breeze blows soft and light;
The autumn dew is cool and white.
Their plaintive notes like music ring;
Their dense hues make jade blossoms spring.
In bitter frost and snow they stand,
Alone displaying green so grand.
Do they not mind the freezing air?
They scorn spring blooms, so proud and fair.
Spring blooms may flourish and decay;
Their steadfast green will never sway.

The Weaving Maid and Cowherd see off the setting sun;
They gaze, not knowing the Magpie Bridge is long outrun.
What saddens most is the song of parting tonight;
Looking afar, heart-broken, they lose each other in sight.

The tribesmen in the borderland are well-armed and well-dressed;
They hunt along the Yellow River from morning till night's rest.
The northern song is not yet ended when wild geese fly overhead;
Their horses neigh on grassland green where their flocks and herds are fed.

Beneath kind breeze, the buds like pearls appear;
Before spring comes, the golden sprouts are dear.
Fresh leaves are baked and packed with fragrant care,
So fine and good, yet not beyond compare.
For kings and lords, such tea is a delight;
How comes it to my hut so poor and slight?
My wicket gate is closed to vulgar guest;
In gauze cap, I brew tea with zest.
Like azure cloud, the steam won't disperse in flight;
Like white flower, it sheds on cup its light.

The temple fragrant, night forgets to go;
Pines fresh, the ancient hall's door sways slow.
The abbot's room with lamplight glows;
On monk's robe beads in strings repose.
By day the heart's pure message spreads;
Blue lotus tells where Dharma leads.
Celestial blooms fall without end;
Birds fly with petals to extend.

Seven mysteries I hold, unknown to me;
How could others know? Let them see.
Call me rich or poor, I care not a bit;
Wise or foolish, I'm content with it.
Strong or weak, I stand as I am;
Hasty or lazy, I give no damn.

In writing, no skill I command;
In fencing, no mastery in hand.
In honor, I fail to stand;
In prose, no grace in my hand.
In Tao or Buddha, no insight I find;
In farming or gardening, no craft of mind.
Call me prodigal, worthless, or stubborn soul,
A dull scholar, a sleepyhead, a lifeless ghoul.

Knowing it's a dream, I wake with no desire;
To lonely peak I go, my ashes to expire.
No clouds can stain the azure sky so vast and deep;
In tranquil air the moonbeams flow, a silver sweep.
Spare me disciples' visits to this stony place,
Where I'll embrace the void with calm and silent grace.

For sorrows deep, the heart grows cold;
For joys in store, the spirit bold.
When hearts are cold, fear takes its hold;
When spirits bold, brave tales are told.
Fear leads to ways of compromise;
Boldness to ventures, grand and wise.
Compromise may the world erase;
Venture can build a better place.

