原文：
唯多忧也，故灰心；唯行乐也，故丧气；唯灰心也，故怯懦；唯怯懦也，故豪壮；唯豪壮也，故苟且；唯苟且也，故冒险；故能灭世界，为冒险也；故能造世界。

译文：
Only with sorrow, one's heart grows cold;
Only with joy, one's spirit fades away;
Only with coldness, one's courage wanes;
Only with wane, one's strength grows bold;
Only with boldness, one's spirit dares;
Only with dares, one's path becomes bold;
Thus, one can destroy the world, for boldness is the way;
Thus, one can create the world.

s2tt:
From northern sea the dark wind sweeps the ground;
On Dragon Mound the king's fair temple's found.
The dead were warriors on the wall;
At dusk their ashes fly o'er the battleground.

Blood stains the blade, the siege drags on for years;
Yet arms are laid aside by wisdom of the sage.
In vain the general burns the bulls with spears;
One arrow wins the battle for the counselor.

Fresh bathed, in light cap I appear;
At dawn the pool's breeze chills and clear.
In harmony with world apart,
I stroll with you, serene at heart.
Rosy clouds disperse, peaks tower high;
Sky boundless, hear wild geese cry.
Let worldly cares to men in power fall;
I'd live in peace like sage of old.

To rule the common, how?  
Talent serves no foolish lord;  
The common follow no wise lord.  
To rule the talent, be bright;  
To rule the common, be humble.  
Promote them, leave none behind;  
Employ them, be not too harsh.  
Treat them well, never meager;  
Punish them, never too light.  
On ruling scholars, part three:  
To rule men, rule scholars first;  
To rule scholars, rule their hearts.  
Respect scholars, harmony thrives.

Esteem the wise, and friends you'll gain;
Despise the wise, and chaos reign.
Insult the wise, foes will arise.
Rule by culture, subtle and wise;
Rule by force, no strength will rise.
Honor them, your honor stays;
Debase them, your worth decays.

On Loyalty, Chapter Four:
Loyalty is straight, unguided, strait;
Loyalty is fierce, unguided, plight.

Ninety spring days like dreams pass by;
Each inch of land 'neath the blue sky
Is a soul-consuming place.
At sunset over fields yellow butterflies fly;
Amid dark green ancient locusts and reeds sway.
The farewell song on flute grieves me deep down;
E'en the plaintive song of orchid and clover crown
Is not so sad as this.
My tears o'erflow the broidered word;
In life only love can't die, I've heard.

Thunder roared last night by rivershore;
In spring town rain brings chill we can't ignore.
Two orioles sit, wet, with grief o'erflow;
White egrets fly, too dry, in haste they go.
In later years I'm versed in verse with care;
From door to door I seek for wine to share.
You are the only one who loves me still,
And read my verse with ever fresh good will.

To preach the truth, he mounts the seat high;
The temple gate is closed to passers-by.
Who knows the news is spread far and nigh?
The thunderous sound shakes the earth and sky.
The crowd sweeps all the temples clean and bare;
The streets are thronged with chariots here and there.
The temple's full, outside there's no more room;
The latecomers can't hear in the gloom.
They take off jewels and hairpins with pleasure,
Piling up gold and jade in dazzling treasure.

Ill in autumn by the sea I lie;
The Double Ninth will see wind and rain sweep the sky.
My door has long been mossy, none comes to see;
I feel so sad alone at the end of the sea.
I planted by the fence chrysanthemums yellow;
Why don't they bloom when comes the happy fellow?
They must have reasons for their fragrance to withhold;
Last night you asked for poems, I was told.
At dawn I send you roots with frost aglow;
Though humble as a spadeful of jade, I hope you'll know.

Wind stirs tall bamboo, coolness grows;
Rain brings lotus scent, fresh it flows.
Fish swim, worldly nets they outgrow;
Birds sing, Zen taste begins to show.
One stroke cures all ills, wisdom's might;
Mind's blade cuts free, boundless in sight.
When sick, I oft shunned guests with dread;
Now, for their coming, heart is led.

Hills drip haze, waves lap the shore;
Grass sweet, sand warm, no mud any more.
Am I lost in a fairy stream?
Peach blossoms redden in sunbeam;
Willows green hang like a screen.
A cup of wine, a hundred years' dream.

High lords in golden banners ride;
Who cares for an old man's black hood?
The mirror tells the truth I hide;
Apricot branches show spring's mood.
In bed I hear my children say
My verse is fresh as is the day.

A quiet inn with ancient gate shut tight;
Again I rest in empty hall, my robe worn through.
The roc transformed in flight for ninety thousand li;
The crane came back after a thousand years, it's true.
Around the courtyard bamboos shoot up with new sprouts;
I measure with my belt the pine's old girth anew.
Only the verse on the wall remains in view,
Where dust dims ink and both are clinging to.

White hair, like withered grass, would cover my head;
Returning, thrice I've seen my native hills in autumn's hue.
Drunk, I lean on the tower, feeling the world's narrow spread;
Sick, I'm in midlife, yet sun and moon still swiftly sped.
In iron armor, through a hundred battles, for my country vainly I've pled;
At the fifth watch, the painted horn only brings sorrow anew.
Tomorrow, by misty rain on Tong River's shore, my boat I'll moor instead,
And tie it to a crimson maple, where I'll fish in solitude's quiet bed.

The north wind withers the white grass low;
The Tartar steeds southward daily go.
The moon shines bright on watch-towers high;
The autumn saddens the frontier vie.
Their iron armor frost and dew weight;
Their steeds grow old in battles great.
Since the fortress was built long ago,
Dust and smoke have been seen to blow.

The hall's curtains dispel the heat's might;  
The royal path holds autumn's dim light.  
A mournful wind moves the Han lute's strain;  
Flowing waters join the Qin lyre's refrain.  
Clouds drift, sending off wild geese in flight;  
The moon rises, cleansing sparse woods bright.  
Dripping dew from branches softly sings;  
Misty vales deepen where mystery clings.

Purple plums, green melons sweeten country road;
Black gauze, white flax cool the Taoist robe.
In wild temple, pine shades shift behind closed door;
On breeze-swept couch, the guest dreams long and more.
Illness-gained leisure is no curse, I find;
Peace of mind is the best cure for mankind.
The monk spares not the water before the stair,
But lends the gourd ladle for me to share.

Gold and gems in heaps lie low;
Jade and pearls in halls o'erflow.
Sweet osmanthus streams flow by;
Waves on waves surge up to the sky.
Turtles leap and dance with glee;
Cranes fly back and forth with glee.
Leaning on rails, I gaze afar,
Longing for you, my lord, afar.
Grief and sorrow gnaw my heart;
Deep in my heart I feel the smart.
Heaven's gate and earth's door close the way.
Who can show the sages the way?

The waves of Han River flow afar;
The clouds o'er Witch Hill drift and fly.
The east wind blows my dream where you are;
It sets in west when I wake and sigh.
Awake, I think of the White Emperor's Town,
Where my fair one is severed from me.
Merchants oft in Gorge go up and down;
O let them bring your news to me!

The waves of Han River flow afar;
The clouds o'er Witch Hill drift and fly.
The east wind blows my dream where you are;
It sets in west when I wake and sigh.
Awake, I think of the White Emperor's Town,
Where my fair one is severed from me.
Merchants oft in Gorge go up and down;
O let them bring your news to me!

When autumn comes, how clear the moon!
When moon appears, how bright the autumn!
How can a roving wife in her bower
Not be grieved at this lonely hour?
The dew has dried up orchid sweet;
The frost has covered courtyard floor.
She sits and sees her girdle long;
She turns and finds her waist not strong.
The autumn stream ripples like her eye;
The autumn cloud veils like her dress.
The sun sinks down in western sky;
The wind blows over riverside.

Jade phoenix sings sweet in the tower of flowers;
Red silk veil smells faint with embroidered bowers.
Yellow swan dances to the toast of a thousand years;
Fairy candles flicker with smoke light as tears.
Clear lute and drunken eyes are drowned in crystal springs.

Jade phoenix sings sweet in the tower of flowers;
Red silk veil smells faint with embroidered bowers.
Yellow swan dances to the toast of a thousand years;
Fairy candles flicker with smoke light as tears.
Clear lute and drunken eyes are drowned in crystal springs.

The northern slope of Mount Zhongnan looks fair;
Its snow-crowned peaks are floating in the air.
The forest bright in sunset glow appears;
The evening cold invades the town with ease.

A crescent moon hangs o'er the willow bay;
The Southern hills are mirrored in the spray.
Three days of rain have washed peach blossoms down;
At midnight leap the carps to reach the town.

All trees are frozen, about to break;
Alone the root feels warmth and starts to wake.
In deep snow of the village ahead,
Last night one branch of mume bloomed outspread.
The wind sends its secret fragrance far;
Birds peep at its white bloom, wondering what they are.
Next year it should flower as by law;
First on Spring Terrace you'll see it thaw.

From far-off hills no message came;
Through winter long, then spring the same.
Nearing homeland, timid I grow;
I dare not ask what I would know.

Night-blooming flowers scent the courtyard deep;
At dead of night, light rain sobers me from sleep.
How to send word to friends far, far away?
How to recall old griefs of bygone day?
The children then have now grown up full-blown;
Half of my old friends have passed away, alone.
Tomorrow I'll leave by lonely boat again;
The wine shop's green flag will augment my pain.
